"1355","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1406":"1406","Balwearie Castle, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland","Balwearie Castle, Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Scott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (Down): habitational and ethnic name from Middle English <i>Scot</i> ‘man from Scotland’. There is no evidence that the surname denoted either of the earlier senses of <i>Scot</i> as ‘(Gaelic-speaking) Irishman’ or ‘man from Alba’, the Gaelic-speaking region of Scotland north of the river Forth. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English and Scottish: from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Scot</i> (Old English <i>Scott</i>, possibly also Old Norse <i>Skotr</i>), only certainly attested in northern England.","English: variant of   Scutt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Scutt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Pierre.","Americanized form of Dutch   Schutte   ‘archer’.","English: nickname for a short person, from Middle English <i>scut(e)</i> ‘short’, or else for a swift runner, from Middle English <i>scut</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Andrew Scott - Fourth Lord of Balwearie was born in 1315, in Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland, his father, Sir Henry Scott - Third Lord of Balweary, was 40 and his mother, Mrs. Henry Scott, was 36. He married Lady Isobel de Warren in 1340, in Brabourne, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1355, in his hometown, at the age of 40, and was buried in Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland."},"et":{"1315–1355":"1315–1355","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1350–1406":"1350–1406","1275–1330":"1275–1330","1279–Female":"1279–Surnud","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1406":"1406","Balwearie Castle, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland","Balwearie Castle, Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1315–1355":"1315–1355","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1350–1406":"1350–1406","1275–1330":"1275–1330","1279–Female":"1279–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1406":"1406","Balwearie Castle, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland","Balwearie Castle, Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England"},"fr":{"1315–1355":"1315–1355","1310–Female":"1310–Décédée","1350–1406":"1350–1406","1275–1330":"1275–1330","1279–Female":"1279–Décédée","1315":"1315","1279":"1279","135